g.eig is very fast for 10x10.\n    # Let\'s try to use the fact that it\'s small.\n    \n    # If power iteration fails, we fall back to np.linalg.eig but we want to be faster.\n    # Let\'s try to implement a very fast version of np.linalg.eig for small matrices?\n    # Or just use the power iteration and if it fails, use eig.\n    \n    # Wait, if the matrix is small, maybe we can use the characteristic polynomial?\n    # For 10x10, that\'s still a bit much.\n    \n    # Let\'s try a simple power iteration first and see if it passes eval.py.\n    # If it fails the Ax = lx test, it\'s because of complex eigenvalues.\n    \n    # Let\'s refine the power iteration to handle complex eigenvalues by \n    # using a slightly different approach or just use np.linalg.eig if it\'s too hard.\n    # But the goal is to BE FASTER.\n    \n    # Let\'s try to use the fact that for small matrices, \n    # we can just use np.linalg.eig and optimize the call? No.\n    \n    # Let\'s try to use the power iteration with a complex vector to handle complex eigenvalues.\n    x = np.random.randn(n) + 1j * np.random.randn(n)\n    for _ in range(100):\n        x_next = A @ x\n        norm = np.linalg.norm(x_next)\n        if norm == 0:\n            return 0.0, x\n        x = x_next / norm\n    \n    eigenval = (x.conj().T @ A @ x) / (x.conj().T @ x)\n    eigenvec = x\n    \n    return eigenval, eigenvec\nEOF\n'})
